Kubernetes Metrics Server Setup & Troubleshooting Guide
1. Metrics Server Overview

Purpose:
The Metrics Server collects resource usage data (CPU, memory) from nodes and pods. It's required for commands like:

kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods

Without it, these commands fail or show no data.

2. Prerequisites

Kubernetes cluster up and running (v1.32.x in your case)

All nodes in Ready state:

kubectl get nodes -o wide

Network plugin (Calico, Flannel, etc.) properly installed

Kubelet running on all nodes

3. Installing Metrics Server

Download or create the Metrics Server manifest:

curl -LO https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml

Or create a custom manifest metrics-server-fix.yaml.

Apply the manifest:

kubectl apply -f metrics-server-fix.yaml

Restart deployment to ensure new configuration is applied:

kubectl rollout restart deployment metrics-server -n kube-system
4. Recommended Configuration Fixes

Host networking if your cluster has network policies blocking pod-to-pod communication:

spec:
  hostNetwork: true
  dnsPolicy: ClusterFirst

Kubelet insecure TLS if self-signed certs are used:

args:
  - --kubelet-insecure-tls

Node Selector to control placement (optional):

nodeSelector:
  kubernetes.io/hostname: worker1

Custom Port (default 443), match host firewall:

args:
  - --secure-port=4443
ports:
  - containerPort: 4443

Probes:

livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /livez
    port: https
    scheme: HTTPS
readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /readyz
    port: https
    scheme: HTTPS
5. Verifying Installation

Check Metrics Server pods:

kubectl get pods -n kube-system -l k8s-app=metrics-server -o wide

Check APIService:

kubectl get apiservice v1beta1.metrics.k8s.io -o wide

AVAILABLE=True → Metrics Server is functioning

AVAILABLE=False → Something is wrong (TLS, network, pods pending)

Check metrics:

kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods -A
6. Common Issues & Troubleshooting
Issue	Symptoms	Fix
Pod in Pending	No node selected	Check nodeSelector or available resources
Pod in ContainerCreating	Volume mount/network issue	Ensure hostNetwork=true, proper volumes defined
Pod in Error	Kubelet TLS or port issues	Use --kubelet-insecure-tls and match secure-port
APIService False	Metrics API not reachable	Ensure Metrics Server pod is Running and network allows access
Port conflicts	Metrics Server can't start	Change --secure-port to an unused port (e.g., 4443)
7. Step-by-Step Recovery Example

Delete failing pods:

kubectl delete pod -n kube-system -l k8s-app=metrics-server

Re-apply the manifest:

kubectl apply -f metrics-server-fix.yaml

Restart deployment:

kubectl rollout restart deployment metrics-server -n kube-system

Watch pod status:

kubectl get pods -n kube-system -l k8s-app=metrics-server -o wide --watch

Check APIService:

kubectl get apiservice v1beta1.metrics.k8s.io -o wide

Verify metrics:

kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods -A
8. Notes & Best Practices

Always ensure metrics-server version matches your Kubernetes version

If using network policies, allow pod-to-pod traffic for port 443/4443

For multi-node clusters, hostNetwork: true often fixes connectivity issues

Keep a backup of your manifest for easy restoration
